#compdef bcryptjs
# ============================================================================
# bcryptjs - bcrypt hash generator CLI using the pure-JS
#             bcryptjs library (JavaScript -> Node, MIT)
#
# Author : Ilkka Myller (imyller)
# Upstream: https://github.com/imyller/node-bcryptjs-cli
# npm    : bcryptjs-cli (binary: bcryptjs)
#
# `bcryptjs` is a minimal CLI for generating bcrypt
# hashes via the `bcryptjs` pure-JavaScript bcrypt
# library. It accepts a plaintext password as a CLI
# argument + an optional salt round count, generates
# the bcrypt salt internally, computes the hash, and
# writes the resulting $2a$ MCF string to stdout.
#
# Usage:
#   bcryptjs <password> [salt-rounds]
#   bcryptjs "hunter2"             # default cost 10
#   bcryptjs "hunter2" 12          # cost 12
#
# Args:
#   <password>      - plaintext password to hash
#   [salt-rounds]   - bcrypt cost factor (4-31;
#                      default 10; values outside
#                      the range are clamped)
#
# The cost factor maps directly to bcrypt's adaptive
# work factor parameter (log2 of iteration count).
# At cost 10 the hash function takes ~100ms per
# computation on modern hardware (the OWASP 2024
# baseline). At cost 12 it takes ~400ms, suitable
# for high-security deployments. Values above ~14
# become noticeable for interactive logins.
#
# The bcryptjs lane is built on the `bcryptjs` npm
# package (declared at upstream package.json HEAD as
# `bcryptjs: latest`), the canonical *pure-JavaScript*
# Node bcrypt library by Daniel Wirtz (dcodeIO) and
# the @dcodeIO maintenance team - github.com/
# dcodeIO/bcrypt.js, 3700+ stars on the underlying
# library.
#
# bcryptjs is the *pure-JS sibling* of kelektiv/
# node.bcrypt.js (the native-binding variant). The
# Node ecosystem has TWO parallel canonical bcrypt
# libraries with intentionally different
# performance + compatibility tradeoffs:
#
#   1. kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js (npm `bcrypt`):
#      - native N-API binding to OpenBSD's reference
#        C bcrypt implementation
#      - ~10x faster than pure-JS at the same cost
#        factor (because native CPU instructions
#        vs JS-emulated bit operations)
#      - REQUIRES native compilation toolchain on
#        install (node-gyp + a C compiler)
#      - DOES NOT work in: browser bundles,
#        Cloudflare Workers, AWS Lambda layers
#        without custom runtime, mobile React Native
#        builds
#
#   2. dcodeIO/bcrypt.js (npm `bcryptjs`):
#      - pure-JavaScript implementation
#      - ~10x slower than kelektiv at the same cost
#        factor (so cost 10 -> ~1 second per hash
#        in pure-JS vs ~100ms native)
#      - NO native compilation required - works
#        in browser + Cloudflare Workers + AWS
#        Lambda + React Native + every JS runtime
#      - byte-for-byte wire-format compatible with
#        kelektiv's hashes (both produce $2a$ /
#        $2b$ MCF-format strings that the other
#        decodes correctly)
#
# Projects choose between them based on the deployment
# target:
#   - server-side Node with control over native deps
#     -> kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js (better perf)
#   - serverless / browser / edge / RN -> bcryptjs
#     (no native compilation required)
#   - libraries that must work in both contexts ->
#     usually bcryptjs (broader compatibility, accept
#     the perf penalty)
#
# bcryptjs (THIS BINARY) uses `bcryptjs.genSalt(rounds,
# cb)` + `bcryptjs.hash(str, salt, cb)` from the
# pure-JS library - the binary itself runs in pure
# JS, so it inherits the pure-JS tradeoff (slower
# but universally portable).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 254 :: bcrypt password hashing (Provos +
#              Mazières 1999, OpenBSD origin;
#              adaptive cost factor)
# Round 1462 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 254
#                                       (247th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : Keats/rust-bcrypt           [R1460 _floundr]
#   Go      : golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt  [R1461 _bcrypter]
#             (core-team subrepo)
#   TS/Node : kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js     [R1462 THIS FILE]
#             (native) + dcodeIO/bcrypt.js
#             (pure-JS) - dual canonical
#
# The Node slot closes Axis 254 with the *dual-
# canonical-by-deployment-target* pattern. Unlike the
# Rust + Go slots (each with a single dominant
# canonical), the Node ecosystem has two parallel
# canonicals chosen by deployment context:
#
#   - kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js (native binding):
#     server-side Node with native-compile toolchain
#     access; ~10x faster
#   - dcodeIO/bcrypt.js / bcryptjs (pure-JS):
#     serverless + browser + edge + React Native;
#     ~10x slower but universally portable
#
# Both produce byte-identical wire-format bcrypt
# hashes that cross-verify identically. The choice
# is purely about install-surface (native compile
# toolchain availability) + runtime perf, not
# spec-compliance.
#
# This dual-canonical pattern at Axis 254 mirrors
# Axis 245 (BLAKE3) where the Node slot has
# connor4312/blake3 (Wasm binding) + @node-rs/blake3
# (napi-rs binding to Rust) as parallel canonicals.
# Both axes reflect Node's broader pattern of
# multiple-implementation diversity for performance-
# sensitive primitives, with selection driven by
# deployment context.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# bcrypt $2a$ / $2b$ hash produced by rust-bcrypt +
# x/crypto/bcrypt + kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js +
# dcodeIO/bcrypt.js + the OpenBSD reference C
# implementation verifies byte-identically across all
# canonical implementations.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - floundr (Rust, Keats/rust-bcrypt): OCI
#     container registry server with bcrypt-hashed
#     user accounts
#   - bcrypter (Go, x/crypto/bcrypt): minimal stdin-
#     to-stdout bcrypt hash generator
#   - bcryptjs (Node, dcodeIO/bcrypt.js): pure-JS
#     bcrypt hash CLI with configurable cost
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (full server /
# stdin hasher / arg-driven hasher), three
# implementation strategies (single canonical Rust /
# single core-team-subrepo Go / dual-canonical
# native-vs-pure-JS Node), all converging on the
# OpenBSD reference bcrypt wire format + the
# Provos-Mazières 1999 algorithm specification.
#
# Axis 254 closes the round 1462 cycle - 247th axis
# closed total.
# ============================================================================

_bcryptjs() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '1:password:' \
        '2:salt rounds (4-31, default 10):(4 6 8 10 12 14)'
}

_bcryptjs "$@"
